you can ignore the import error message. we should remove that. even though it says only 64bit is supported, it does indeed work on 32bit as well. see https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/590
I think the error message you're encountering is saying you don't have numpy module installed.

re: 64bit arm on jetson, you can build natively (don't cross compile) on jetson ,and it should work. 
we haven't tested on jetson tx2 specifically, but we have tested a fair amount on jetson nano.
see https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/995
will close as the issue seems resolved.

Maybe it has to do with building in a different directory than where you cloned the source? Perhaps there is some built in assumption about relative paths.

Here is the steps I take:

```
git clone --recursive https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime
cd onnxruntime
export CUDACXX="/usr/local/cuda/bin/nvcc"
Modify CMakeLists.txt
    -  set(CMAKE_CUDA_FLAGS "${CMAKE_CUDA_FLAGS} -gencode=arch=compute_50,code=sm_50") # M series
    +  set(CMAKE_CUDA_FLAGS "${CMAKE_CUDA_FLAGS} -gencode=arch=compute_53,code=sm_53") # Jetson support

./build.sh --config Release --update --build --build_wheel --use_tensorrt --cuda_home /usr/local/cuda --cudnn_home /usr/lib/aarch64-linux-gnu --tensorrt_home /usr/lib/aarch64-linux-gnu

```
